From 78a827c39a1b80c7a36c79b7d4ca4c1e11f3dc6c Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Volker Badziong <development@richtfest.tech>
Date: Fri, 17 Jul 2026 09:48:27 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 8/8] Report configuration keys discarded while parsing

Wings parses config.yml permissively and then rewrites the file from the
parsed struct at boot. A key the schema does not define -- most often a
real key at the wrong indentation, landing under the wrong parent or at
the document root -- is therefore accepted, silently ignored, and then
erased from the file by the rewrite. The administrator is left with a
configuration that looks untouched and a setting that never took effect,
with no diagnostic anywhere. Duplicate mapping keys are lost the same
way, the last occurrence quietly winning over everything set earlier.

Re-decode the raw bytes with UnmarshalStrict purely as a diagnostic, and
log every discarded key once at startup: after initLogging so it reaches
the normal log pipeline, and before the rewrite in rootCmdRun removes the
evidence.

The permissive decode stays authoritative. A strict decode would turn a
stale key left over from an older Wings into a boot failure, so unknown
keys must warn, never fail.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
